16:["$","aside",null,{"className":"mt-8 rounded-2xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-500/[0.07] p-6","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"mb-3 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-indigo-300","children":"TL;DR"}],["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex gap-2.5 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-neutral-200","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-1 text-indigo-400","aria-hidden":true,"children":"▸"}],"ADHD attention is interest-gated, not effort-gated — a boring chapter doesn't respond to trying harder."]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex gap-2.5 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-neutral-200","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-1 text-indigo-400","aria-hidden":true,"children":"▸"}],"Three specific mechanisms stop you: initiation friction, time blindness, and working-memory overload."]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex gap-2.5 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-neutral-200","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-1 text-indigo-400","aria-hidden":true,"children":"▸"}],"The fix is structural, not motivational: bound the task in time, break it into 5-minute checkpoints, and read with your ears and eyes together."]}]]}]]}]
1a:Te56,<p>It&#39;s 11pm. The chapter is due at 9am. You&#39;ve read the first paragraph four times, and you could not repeat one sentence of it back.</p>
<p>If that scene is familiar, here&#39;s the part nobody told you: <strong>that&#39;s not a discipline problem — it&#39;s a mismatch between how the task is shaped and how your attention works.</strong> And reshaping the task is a lot easier than reshaping your brain.</p>
<h2>Your attention is interest-gated, not effort-gated</h2>
<p>Most study advice assumes attention is a muscle you push harder. ADHD attention doesn&#39;t work that way — it&#39;s closer to a gate that opens for <strong>interest, novelty, urgency, or challenge</strong>, and stays shut for everything else, no matter how important the thing behind it is.</p>
<p>That&#39;s why you can hyperfocus for four hours on something you love and bounce off two pages of a required reading. <strong>The chapter isn&#39;t harder. It just doesn&#39;t open the gate.</strong></p>
<p>So the goal isn&#39;t to force the gate. It&#39;s to change the shape of the reading until it triggers the things the gate responds to.</p>
<h2>The three mechanisms actually stopping you</h2>
<p><strong>1. Initiation friction.</strong> Starting is a separate neurological event from doing, and it&#39;s the one ADHD taxes hardest. An unbounded task — &quot;read chapter seven&quot; — has no edges, so your brain can&#39;t find the handle.</p>
<p><strong>2. Time blindness.</strong> Without a felt sense of duration, that chapter is simply <em>infinite</em>. Nobody starts infinite tasks at 11pm. The moment a reading has a number on it — <strong>&quot;this is 26 minutes at your speed&quot;</strong> — it becomes a container instead of a fog.</p>
<p><strong>3. Working-memory overload.</strong> Reading holds sentences in a mental buffer while your eyes fetch the next one. When attention dips, the buffer drops — which is precisely the reread-the-paragraph loop. You didn&#39;t fail to read it. <strong>The buffer emptied before the sentence finished.</strong></p>
<h2>The structural fix (the 26-minute method)</h2>
<p>None of this responds to motivation. All of it responds to structure:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Bound it.</strong> Get a real time number on the reading before you start. A 47-minute chapter at 1.8× speed is 26 minutes. Say the number out loud. You&#39;re no longer starting &quot;chapter seven&quot; — you&#39;re starting 26 minutes.</li>
<li><strong>Checkpoint it.</strong> Break the container into ~5-minute sections with a marker between them. Every checkpoint is a finish line, and each one you pass is a small, real completion — the thing ADHD motivation actually runs on.</li>
<li><strong>Double-code it.</strong> Listen <em>and</em> watch the words highlight at the same time. When your visual attention drifts (it will), the audio carries the thread; when your mind snaps back, the highlight shows exactly where to land. The reread loop dies here.</li>
<li><strong>Add a floor of sound.</strong> Steady brown noise under the voice gives the restless part of your attention something to hold, like a weighted blanket for your ears. Test it on one chapter — many ADHD readers never go back.</li>
</ul>
<p>We built <a href="/dashboard">Hyperfi</a> to do all four automatically — time math on every document, spoken checkpoints every five minutes, karaoke-style highlighting, and a noise bed under the voice. But the method is bigger than any tool: <strong>bound it, chunk it, double-code it, and stop treating a structural mismatch like a moral failing.</strong></p>
<p>You&#39;ve been trying to fix yourself. Fix the task instead.</p>
